<TITLE> Czech ex-president Havel taken to hospital </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PRAGUE, Jan 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Former Czech President Vaclav Havel was taken to hospital with a heart problem but is feeling well, Czech television reported on Sunday. Havel, 71, was admitted to hospital on Saturday with heart arrhythmia, the television said. "The hospitalisation is temporary," Havel's personal secretary Jakub Hladik told the television. "At the moment he is feeling well and we hope his condition will improve," he said. The former leading anti-communist dissident and playwright was elected Czechoslovak president in the bloodless 1989 Velvet Revolution which ended four decades of communist rule. He became Czech president in 1993 after the split of Czechoslovakia, and led the central European country until 2003, overseeing its integration with western Europe. Havel's health has been poor for years and he nearly died after a lung cancer operation and an intestine rupture in the 1990s. Since he stepped down from the presidency, Havel has devoted time to supporting human rights activists in countries such as Cuba and Myanmar. He has also returned to writing, and published a new play due to be premiered later this ye
